    "summary": "The Christianization of Kievan Rus (988 AD) — when Prince Vladimir I of Kiev ordered the mass baptism of his people in the Dnieper River and smashed the pagan idols of Perun and other gods — was among the most consequential religious conversions in history, bringing Orthodox Christianity (and with it Byzantine culture, art, writing, and law) to the Slavic world and setting the cultural foundation of Russia, Ukraine, and Belarus. According to the Primary Chronicle, Vladimir chose among Judaism, Islam, Western Christianity, and Eastern Orthodoxy by sending emissaries to each. The emissaries reportedly came back most impressed by the Hagia Sophia in Constantinople, saying: 'We knew not whether we were in heaven or on earth.'\n\nVladimir's choice was as much political as spiritual: an alliance with Byzantium through Christianity, sealed by his marriage to Byzantine princess Anna Porphyrogenita, gave Kievan Rus access to Byzantine trade, diplomatic legitimacy, and cultural prestige. Byzantine missionaries brought the Cyrillic alphabet (devised by Saints Cyril and Methodius for the Slavic languages), translated scriptures and liturgy, and established the church infrastructure that would make Orthodox Christianity the cultural backbone of the Slavic world. The decision to align with Constantinople rather than Rome had lasting consequences: when the Great Schism of 1054 split Christianity, Rus was in the Eastern Orthodox camp, creating the cultural and civilizational divide between western and eastern Europe that persists to this day.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christianization_of_Kievan_Rus%27",
